==English==

===Etymology 1===
From the name of the beautiful orange fossil resin [[amber]]; from Middle English [[ambre]], from Old French [[ambre]], from Latin [[ambar]], from the Arabic عنبر (''‘anbar'', meaning ''[[amber]]'').

====Alternative spellings====
*[[Ambre]] (French)

====Pronunciation====
*''(US)'' {{AHD|/ăm'bər/}}, {{IPA|/ˈæmbər/}}
*''(RP)'' {{IPA|/ˈæmbə/}}

*:Hyphenation: '''Am-ber'''
*:Rhymes: ''(RP)'' [[Rhymes:English:-ˈæmbə|-ˈæmbə]], ''(US)'' [[Rhymes:English:-ˈæmbər|-ˈæmbər]]
*:Homophones: [[amber]]

====Proper noun====
'''Amber'''
# a [[female]] [[given name]]
#* '''1923''' [[CE]]: Israel Zangwill, ''The Grey Wig''
#*: ''"I love his letters," gushed '''Amber''', bafflingly. "He writes such cute things."''
# a [[male]] [[given name]]
#* '''1901''' [[CE]]: Frederick Swainson, ''Acton's Feud''
#*: ''I soon saw that the school was not quite good enough for the others [...] '''Amber''', the half, generally waltzed round our forwards''.

